I had a look at this issue again and I think this is hard limitation of Java/Swing.

Take this class for example:
```
public class Test {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		JFrame frame = new JFrame();
		frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
		frame.setBounds(100, 100, 10000, 10000);
		frame.setVisible(true);
	}
}
```

If you run this class (without WindowBuilder, just as a normal Java application), then the frame will be maximized and take up your entire screen (which most likely has a smaller resolution than 10000x10000). So to answer your initial question:
The maximum width and height of a JFrame is defined by (java.awt.)Toolkit.getScreenSize().

Which means there is little that can be fixed on our site. The documentation should probably be updated, to include this limitation and the preview in the design page should also be limited to that size.

