Thanks! The profiler snapshot is already enough to give me a general idea of what's going on.

WindowBuilder is most likely getting stuck while executing the call to `super.dispose()`, i.e. while executing Java-internal code.

As for the reasons, I can only speculate, but I believe that this is a deadlock caused by both the SWT UI thread and the Swing UI thread trying to acquire the same lock.

I would assume that this problem not only shows up with the JDialog but also the JFrame. More so, I would also assume that this is problem is not limited to WindowBuilder but a general problem when mixing SWT and Swing, for example when doing something like this (though perhaps with some additional tweaks):

```
public class Snippet {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Shell shell = new Shell();
		Display display = shell.getDisplay();

		shell.setSize(500, 500);
		shell.setText("SWT Shell");
		shell.open();
		display.asyncExec(() -> {
			JFrame frame = new JFrame();
			frame.setSize(500, 500);
			frame.setTitle("Swing JFrame");
			frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(WindowConstants.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
			frame.setVisible(true);
			// ...
			frame.dispose();
		});

		while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
			display.readAndDispatch();
		}
	}
}
```

Given that this doesn't happen on Windows or Linux (which is notorious for locking the UI thread), I'm leaning towards calling this an issue within the JRE. And given that I don't have access to a Mac, I won't really be able to further investigate this problem.

Meaning that in the current state, your best chances to get this fixed is by investigating this issue yourself and if-possible providing a fix.

